50|$|The SM&AR {{purchased}} three 0-6-0 tank locomotives from Dübs and Company for its opening; numbered 1 to 3 {{they had}} 4 feet (1,219 mm) diameter wheels and <b>outside</b> <b>cylinders.</b> Three 2-4-0 tank engines were acquired from Beyer Peacock in 1882 {{and a fourth}} in 1884. These were intended for passenger work and were numbered 5 to 8, having 5 ft 6in (1,616 mm) wheels and <b>outside</b> <b>cylinders.</b> The latter proved more effective for longer hauls.|$|R
50|$|Its last steam {{locomotives}} {{were two}} examples built by Hudswell Clarke & Co. of Leeds: No. 34, an <b>outside</b> <b>cylinder,</b> six-coupled side tank locomotive, works No.1523, built in 1925 and delivered {{new to the}} Appleby-Frodingham Steel Company in Scunthorpe, which came to {{the line in the}} 1950s; and No. 37, an <b>outside</b> <b>cylinder,</b> six-coupled saddle tank. They worked until the mid-1960s, when the line became fully dieselised, Hudswell Clarke again supplying the power.|$|R
